<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-874-198  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 874 198.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Nov 13 1989 v11 n46 p79(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Will Sun binaries run on System V.4? (Sun Microsystems decidingwhether to add translation software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Marshall, Martin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Current Sun operating system applications will be incompatiblewith the new Sun/System V.4 operating system because the newsystem is based on Unix System V, Release 4, which has a number ofdifferent system calls from the Berkeley Unix-based Sun OS 4.0.andO;System V.4 also uses a different file format than the Sun OS.andP;  Thecompany is considering adding translation software to the newoperating system; Sun currently provides a free 'Migration Guideto System V.4' to any software developer, but end users facehaving to acquire and re-install new versions of every applicationfor every Sun system using the new release.andP;  Code embedded in theoperating system would allow translation 'on the fly,' but wouldcause some performance degradation.andP;  Sun expects independentsoftware vendors to quickly produce updates.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Sun Microsystems Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    SUNW.andO;Topic:     UNIXSoftware MigrationCompatibilityMarketing StrategySoftware DesignUpdatingProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>